# Phase 5: Deployment Engine

**Phase:** 5 of 12
**Status:** Not Started
**Depends on:** Phase 4 (Build System) -- Docker images must be built and tagged before the deployment engine can start containers from them
**Blocks:** Phase 6 (Core Dashboard & API) -- API routes trigger deployments; Phase 7 (Preview Deployments) -- preview deploys use the same engine with preview port range; Phase 8 (Caching, Streaming & Rollback) -- rollback reuses Deployer orchestration

---

## Goal

After Phase 4 builds a Docker image and tags it with the commit SHA, the deployment engine takes over: allocate a port, inject environment variables, start the container, health-check it, configure Caddy reverse-proxy routing, stop the old container, and mark the deployment as READY. The app is then live at its subdomain URL (`{project}.yourdomain.dev` for production, `pr-{n}--{project}.yourdomain.dev` for previews).

---

## Context

The deployment engine is the core runtime loop of gBlockParty. The build system (Phase 4) produces an immutable Docker image tagged `{project}:{commit-sha}`. This phase implements everything that happens after the image exists: the container lifecycle, networking, environment injection, and health verification.

### Why This Phase Exists

Without the deployment engine, a built Docker image just sits in the local image cache. This phase connects the image to the live network by:

1. Assigning a unique port so containers don't collide
2. Injecting project-specific environment variables (including decrypted secrets)
3. Starting the container and verifying it is healthy before routing traffic
4. Dynamically updating Caddy so the hostname resolves to the new container
5. Gracefully stopping the old container to avoid downtime
6. Recording the final state in the database so the dashboard can display it

### Architecture Context

```
Phase 4 output: Docker image {project}:{sha}
    |
    v
Phase 5: Deployment Engine
    |
    +-- 1. PortAllocator.allocate(deploymentId, type)
    |       -> finds next free port in range, inserts into port_allocations table
    |
    +-- 2. Env var injection
    |       -> query env_vars table, decrypt secrets, write temp .env file
    |
    +-- 3. docker run -d -p {port}:3000 --env-file .env {project}:{sha}
    |       -> start container, get containerId
    |
    +-- 4. waitForHealthy(containerId, healthCheckPath, port)
    |       -> poll HTTP GET localhost:{port}{path}, retry 10x at 2s intervals
    |
    +-- 5. CaddyClient.addRoute(hostname, port)
    |       -> POST to Caddy admin API, route hostname -> localhost:{port}
    |
    +-- 6. Stop old container (SIGTERM, 30s timeout, SIGKILL)
    |
    +-- 7. Update deployment record: status=READY, url, port, containerId
    |
    +-- 8. Cleanup: delete temp .env file
    |
    v
App is live at https://{project}.yourdomain.dev
```

---

